<h2><a href="/2608" id="entry2608" title="permalink to 'fixed width font in Gmail'">2608</a> fixed width font in Gmail&nbsp;</h2><div class="entry">
  <div id="etext2608"><p style="margin-top: 0;">Does <a href="http://gmail.google.com/">Gmail</a> have a setting somewhere to make message text appear in a fixed width font? 'Cause if it does, I sure can't find it...</p>

<p>To force it to use a fixed width font anyway, I added the following to userContent.css in my <a href="http://www.mozilla.org/products/firefox/">Firefox</a> profile:</p>

<pre class="code">div.msg div.mb {
  font-family: monospace !important;
  font-size: 12px !important;
}</pre>

(Firefox's 'View Selection Source' came in real handy trying to figure out these classnames; regular View Source is a pain on Gmail because the whole thing's Javascript-generated.)</div>
  <div class="entryfooter">
    <div class="date">posted Wednesday, July 21, 2004</div>
    10 comments:    &nbsp;
  </div>
  <div class="inline">
  <h4><a id="comment4990" href="/2608#comment4990">
    1</a>. posted by <a href="http://www.p01.org">P01</a> at 23:19 on
    July 21, 2004    </h4>
  <div class="notetext">
    Per user style sheets have been popular these days.<br />
<br />
Though the chances that that CSS rule may interfere with another site are small, I suggest you to try one of these extensions :<br />
<br />
* URIid ( <a href="http://extensionroom.mozdev.org/more-info/uriid">http://extensionroom.mozdev.org/more-info/uriid</a> ) which adds an id of the form <a href="http://www.milov-nl">www.milov-nl</a> to the body tag of every page you visit.<br />
<br />
<br />
* MyOwnCSS ( <a href="http://www.raphinou.com/cgi-bin/myowncss/main.cgi">http://www.raphinou.com/cgi-bin/myowncss/main.cgi</a> ) does the same as URIid, except that the CSS are stored on an external server and shared between the users. In a way, it the del.icio.us of the CSS customization. <br />
<br />
<br />
Notice, that I haven't tried them yet, but I gonna install URIid and give it a try.  </div>
